                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Although I love Tashim's idea here, I agree with Lyrik about the amount of players who seem to have not played the same game I have.  
<br />

<br />
Get agro != swing away.  SKs should never swing to gain agro, and even moreso with paladins.  If they do, they are either a) brain dead, b) don't care, c) never learned it was a problem, d) trying to kill you.  I'm starting to be of the opinion that a) is the path of least resistance on analyzing this one.  
<br />

<br />
Warriors are a bit tougher... I prefer someone else root the mob (or myself stun/mez/root/whatever) depending on who is in the group.  Most warriors I know use their taunts constantly, so they wait for refresh and rarely have them "up" to try to grab agro with them.   In Hard LDoN, where the mobs don't summon, root should be used gratuitously.  If someone with root sees a free mob, root it, unless its in death snare.  I'm still amazed at how few rangers and paladins I know use their roots to the advantage of the group.  Yes they break.  Yes mez is better.  But, the "chance" that the mob will not move for X seconds means that you just saved someone damage.  
<br />

<br />
Without a high enough charisma, i.e. mines 280, pacification does not land at all in Hard LDoN.  Tried 13 times, 13 resists, but no agro pulls.  So, to pull I use my mezzes, a rooter, and cast sight.  Pulls of 2 are fine obviously; pulls of 3 are handled by mez and root within 2 seconds of initial agro, and more than that in Hard LDoN gets hairy anyway (mobs that triple for 990 hurt, a lot).  But... as long as people figure out what they have and how it fits into a given role, almost anything can be done.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
