                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Rooting in restricted areas isn't a great idea.  It can work, but only with a group that is very used to working together, and to using root for CC - which means one without a regular enchanter.  You need strong root AAs to have a chance that this will hold for more than one or two seconds, btw, which means druid or wizard.  Don't expect a ranger or cleric root to be of more use than a chocolate teapot.
<br />

<br />
The ideal time to use root for CC is on incoming, to space out the mobs.  This isn't going to be possible in all zones, or on all maps.  Otherwise what happens is that all the mobs end up being rooted near the MT - not all precisely on the same spot, just near.  As root breaks, and gets recast, this will be the end result even with root on incoming.  
<br />

<br />
In hard LDoN, you don't want root aggro rules.  The mob will always hit the closest player, regardless of aggro/taunts, etc.  If the player getting hit isn't an MT, at best he'll be a drain on cleric mana, at worst: either he's dead in 10 seconds, or has to move out of range of all the mobs and you've converted 30 second kills into 2 minute kills.
<br />

<br />
I love root: when soloing, or in big, open zones.  Frankly in most groups I just can't persuade the melees to move away from a rooted mob.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
