                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">i see someone here said they use sleep in normal ldon and bliss in high risk. imo, using sleep in normal ldon is a waste of mana. a 65 normal ldon dungeon, all mobs can be mezzed with apath. sleep has no -mr modifier, but just costs extra mana. of course i use bliss in high risk.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The duality of correct and incorrect information in this post is astonishing.
<br />

<br />
Let's lay it out all nice and simple:
<br />

<br />
Apathy: -10 Resist Mod, 30% Memblur, Level Cap 62, 225 Mana
<br />
Sleep: -10 Resist Mod, 35% Memblur, Level Cap 65, 275 Mana
<br />
Bliss: -10 Resist Mod, 40% Memblur, Level Cap 68, 300 Mana
<br />

<br />
Unless for some baffling reason you feel you need the memblur, there is no reason to use any mez other than Apathy in a normal LDoN EVER.  The only mobs you will see in Normal LDoNs which are too high for Apathy are Assassinate bosses and possibly some named - both of which are flagged unmezzable regardless.
<br />

<br />
Similarly, unless you really feel that an extra 5% memblur is critical, there is no reason to use Bliss on a Hard LDoN; All mezzable mobs (which is to say non-named, not boss mobs) in level 65 Hard LDoNs are blue or white.  Which means that the additional level cap on bliss is not needed.
<br />

<br />
And you will not that all three spells have the same resist rate.  Apathy may even have a slightly better one if you believe the old "using a spell 4 levels lower makes it easier to resist" thing, that I swear one of the devs said a long time ago, but I can't seem to find anymore.  But regardless, at the very least, apathy will be resisted exactly the same as sleep, which is resisted exactly the same as bliss.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Without a high enough charisma, i.e. mines 280, pacification does not land at all in Hard LDoN. Tried 13 times, 13 resists, but no agro pulls.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I'd love to tell you that this was a result of your low charisma, but the fact is that charisma has no effect on resist rates on Lulls - only on how often a resist will cause aggro.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">You need strong root AAs to have a chance that this will hold for more than one or two seconds, btw, which means druid or wizard. Don't expect a ranger or cleric root to be of more use than a chocolate teapot. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
As amusing as the concept of a chocolate teapot is, I certainly don't have any strong root AAs, and my roots hold a decent chunk of time in Hard LDoN so long as I use greater fetter for the -30 resist mod.  Since clerics and Rangers both also get a -30 resist mod root, I don't see any reason why their roots should only last one or two seconds.  Sure, the max duration on their roots isn't as long as mine, but 1 minute is still a far cry from a couple of seconds.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
